Dr Eric Mackey
August 25 at 2:51 PM Â·

Governor Kay Ivey has committed $100 million in CARES Act funding to deliver free internet to eligible K-12 students in their homes this fall. ABC for Students will provide free Internet access for eligible students who are enrolled in the National School Lunch Program through their schools and receive free or reduced lunch. This week, families will begin to receive letters with vouchers in the mail. The vouchers will cover equipment and service costs for high-speed Internet service through Dec 2020. Please visit abcstudents.org for more information.

post_text: In the Franklin County Schoolsâ€™ Reopening Plan, which was released last month, it clearly states that masks were not required UNLESS mandated by the Governor, ADPH, or ALSDE. Governor Iveyâ€™s current mask mandate expires August 31. She may extend that mandate, but as of now, we donâ€™t know. Due to that mandate, every child grades 2-12 (except those who suffer from certain medical conditions or disabilities that impede them from wearing a mask) and every employee is required to wear a mask, along with anyone else who enters the school buildings. Face shields are acceptable. Public schools do not have a choice in the matter as of now. We will, however, send out an update as soon as we learn if there is a mask mandate extension or not.

Dr Eric Mackey
July 21 at 11:10 AM Â·

The Alabama State Department of Education has partnered with the University of Alabama to conduct a statewide school technology survey. The purpose of this survey is to build a statewide repository detailing Internet connectivity and Internet-enabled digital device availability to inform decision makers as we expand remote learning capabilities and enhance high-quality instruction to students around the state.

Whether a student is attending school in a traditional classroom setting, virtually, or a blended version of traditional and virtual, it is important that we hear from parents across the state as the survey responses will impact our efforts to respond to ongoing changes relating to remote and blended learning options throughout our state. Please take a few moments to share and complete this statewide school technology survey. The deadline for completing the survey is Friday, July 31, 2020.
http://ow.ly/6ujg50AEdw4

If I have any teacher friends looking for a part time job for the summer, I will be hiring virtual tutors for my UB students who are taking college classes online. The Mark White Show
March 21 at 2:14 PM Â·

I have been very impressed with so many school systems when it comes to feeding students who are currently out of school. Franklin County Schools (Alabama) & their Franklin County Schools Child Nutrition Program is certainly no exception. Yesterday, I saw a post where they had prepared 15,908 meals for 2,651 students! I reached out to Robynn Whitfield Bragwell, who is the director of the child nutrition program for Franklin County Schools, about their effort. She, along with Franklin County Schools Superintendent Greg Hamilton, shared some important information about the child nutrition program and other school information, along with messages to students, parents, and school personnel. Robynn has also offered to give tips to other school systems about how they have organized their effort to feed their students in Franklin County, Alabama. Listen & share.

How many times in your profession have you been truly proud of your job and the group for which you work? Honestly it happens in education a lot. There are lots of small victories you see come to fruition down the road. Many times the work that happens in education has a more long-term payoff. (Much like parenting). In all my 26 years as a teacher, coach and administrator, today was one of the best. I saw a real difference being made with immediate impact. Franklin County Schools handed out 3 days worth of food to over 2600 kids today. In Vina, I saw lunchroom workers, bus drivers, teachers, fellow administrators, maintenance workers and SROs go over and beyond to make sure our kids get their needs met. Iâ€™m thankful to Greg Hamilton (Superintendent) and Robynn Whitfield Bragwell (CNP Director) and Dr Johnny Cleveland (transportation director) for their leadership and planning to get this done. These are trying times, but we will grow and get better from it. FYI: We will continue this effort every Monday until school resumes. Stay safe and God Bless.

Hodges Horse Park
February 26 at 11:49 AM Â·

Hey Everyone! Just wanted to give some more information on our horse camp for anyone wanting to know! HORSES WILL BE PROVIDED! We will be having a horse camp March 21st for ages 4 and up! We will be splitting the age groups up. Ages 4-8 will arrive at 9 and will depart at 1 30. Ages 9 and up will arrive from 2 30- 7 30. The cost is $35 for the day. Parents are welcome to stay if they would like. We will have horse games, crafts, roping, learning basic horse care and of course riding! We will have pizza for lunch, if your child will not eat pizza you might want to pack them a lunch. This will be held at Hodges Equestrian Park. We really hope to have a good turnout! If you plan on letting your child attend please reserve your child a spot as we are only accepting 20 children for each age group. Here are a few ways to book your spot... call the park 205 935 3436, comment on this post, message this facebook page, or message Shelby Harris. Please come join us!

post_text: Please share and inform voters before they go to the polls on March 3, 2020
shared_text:
Tracy Hatton Moore
February 16 at 9:58 AM Â·

Please join me in voting NO to Amendment 1 on March 3rd!! You may be led to believe it promises to help improve education in Alabama, but you are being misled.

Amendment 1 on your March 3rd ballot would take away your right to vote for State School Board and make them all appointed by Gov. Ivey. These POLITICAL appointments would be manipulated by the same BUSINESS interests who started trying to dismantle public education in 2010.... the same interests who want to control the SCHOOL CALENDAR !!!

VOTE NO on Amendment 1 on March 3rd!

The Governor wants you to vote yes on Amendment 1 so SHE can appoint ALL members of the State School Board. Don't do it!!!

Vote NO on March 3rd! Keep your right to vote for or against state school board members.

Please SHARE this with all.
